{ “unitNumber”: 5, “text”: { “title”: “Unit Five: The Present Tense of Regular (and Some Irregular) Verbs”, “sections”: [ { “title”: “Use of the Present Tense”, “paragraphs”: [ { “id”: “5.01”, “content”: “The present tense (or simply ‘the present’) is used to state that an action is occurring at the present time. It corresponds basically to the English simple present (‘I eat’) and present continuous (‘I am eating’):”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Mio padre lavora per la BBC.”, “My father works for the BBC.”], [“Mio padre lavora in giardino.”, “My father’s working in the garden.”], [“Di solito guardo la televisione.”, “Normally I watch TV.”], [“Stasera guardo la televisione.”, “I’m watching TV this evening.”], [“Non guardo la televisione.”, “I don’t watch TV.”], [“Perché non guardi la televisione?”, “Why don’t you watch TV?”], [“Stasera non guardo la televisione.”, “I’m not watching TV this evening.”], [“Perché non guardi la televisione stasera?”, “Why aren’t you watching TV this evening?”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.02”, “content”: “The present can also be used to refer to the future, either the near future or one that is considered fairly certain:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Il treno parte fra cinque minuti.”, “The train leaves/is leaving in five minutes.”], [“Parto domani.”, “I leave/I am leaving tomorrow.”], [“Domani mattina porto Luca alla stazione.”, “Tomorrow morning I’ll take/I’m taking/I’m going to take Luca to the station.”], [“L’estate prossima lavoro con mio zio.”, “Next summer I’ll work/I’m working/going to work with my uncle.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.03”, “content”: “The present is also used to refer to an action which started in the past and is still going on; here, it corresponds to the English present perfect:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Lavoriamo qui da un mese.”, “We’ve been working here for a month.”], [“Mio cugino abita a Roma da tre anni.”, “My cousin’s lived/been living in Rome for three years.”], [“Conosco Giulia da tre anni.”, “I have known Giulia for three years.”], [“Non vedo Dario da mesi.”, “I haven’t seen Dario for months.”] ] } } ] }, { “title”: “The Forms of the Present Tense”, “paragraphs”: [ { “id”: “5.04”, “content”: “Italian verbs are divided into three main groups, the conjugations. The conjugation a verb belongs to is determined by the ending of its infinitive:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“First conjugation”, “Second conjugation”, “Third conjugation”], “rows”: [ [”-are”, “-ere”, “-ire”] ] } }, { “content”: “The forms of the present depend on which conjugation the verb belongs to. The present is formed by changing the ending of the infinitive, as follows:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Person”, “Infinitive in -are”, “Infinitive in -ere”, “Infinitive in -ire”], “rows”: [ [“1st Singular (io)”, “-o”, “-o”, “(-isc)-o”], [“2nd Singular (tu)”, “-i”, “-i”, “(-isc)-i”], [“3rd Singular (lui/lei)”, “-a”, “-e”, “(-isc)-e”], [“1st Plural (noi)”, “-iamo”, “-iamo”, “-iamo”], [“2nd Plural (voi)”, “-ate”, “-ete”, “-ite”], [“3rd Plural (loro)”, “-ano”, “-ono”, “(-isc)-ono”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.05”, “content”: “Regular verbs in -are are conjugated as follows:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Parlare”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “-o”, “parlo”, “I speak”], [”(tu)”, “-i”, “parli”, “you speak”], [”(lui/lei)”, “-a”, “parla”, “he/she/it speaks”], [”(noi)”, “-iamo”, “parliamo”, “we speak”], [”(voi)”, “-ate”, “parlate”, “you speak”], [”(loro)”, “-ano”, “parlano”, “they speak”] ] } }, { “content”: “* As we saw in Unit 4, the subject pronoun is normally omitted in the conjugation of Italian verbs.”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Andrea e Carla lavorano in Italia.”, “Andrea and Carla work in Italy.”], [“Parlo italiano.”, “I speak Italian.”], [“Parlate molto!”, “You talk a lot!”], [“Abitiamo a Genova.”, “We live in Genoa.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.06”, “content”: “Verbs ending in -care and -gare (first conjugation) add h before the endings of the second person singular (-i) and the first person plural (-iamo) in order to keep the hard sound of c and g:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Cercare”, “Pagare”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “cerco”, “I look for”, “pago”, “I pay”], [”(tu)”, “cerchi”, “you look for”, “paghi”, “you pay”], [”(lui/lei)”, “cerca”, “he/she/it looks for”, “paga”, “he/she/it pays”], [”(noi)”, “cerchiamo”, “we look for”, “paghiamo”, “we pay”], [”(voi)”, “cercate”, “you look for”, “pagate”, “you pay”], [”(loro)”, “cercano”, “they look for”, “pagano”, “they pay”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Cerchi Marco?”, “Are you looking for Marco?”], [“Cerchiamo una casa.”, “We’re looking for a house.”], [“Anna paga il conto.”, “Anna pays the bill.”], [“Voi pagate troppo!”, “You pay too much!”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.07”, “content”: “Verbs ending in -ciare and -giare (first conjugation) lose the i before the endings of the second person singular (-i) and the first person plural (-iamo), because the i is not necessary:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Cominciare”, “Mangiare”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “comincio”, “I begin/start”, “mangio”, “I eat”], [”(tu)”, “cominci”, “you begin/start”, “mangi”, “you eat”], [”(lui/lei)”, “comincia”, “he/she/it begins/starts”, “mangia”, “he/she/it eats”], [”(noi)”, “cominciamo”, “we begin/start”, “mangiamo”, “we eat”], [”(voi)”, “cominciate”, “you begin/start”, “mangiate”, “you eat”], [”(loro)”, “cominciano”, “they begin/start”, “mangiano”, “they eat”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Quando cominci il lavoro?”, “When do you start work?”], [“Cominciamo subito.”, “We start right away.”], [“Tu non mangi niente!”, “You don’t eat anything!”], [“Mangiano poco.”, “They don’t eat much.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.08”, “content”: “Verbs ending in -iare (first conjugation) sometimes lose the i before the endings of the second person singular (-i) and the first person plural (-iamo), but the i is kept if it is stressed:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Inviare”, “Mangiare”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “invio”, “I send”, “mangio”, “I eat”], [”(tu)”, “invi”, “you send”, “mangi”, “you eat”], [”(lui/lei)”, “invia”, “he/she/it sends”, “mangia”, “he/she/it eats”], [”(noi)”, “inviamo”, “we send”, “mangiamo”, “we eat”], [”(voi)”, “inviate”, “you send”, “mangiate”, “you eat”], [”(loro)”, “inviano”, “they send”, “mangiano”, “they eat”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Tu invi un’e-mail?”, “Are you sending an e-mail?”], [“Inviamo una lettera.”, “We’re sending a letter.”], [“Tu non mangi niente!”, “You don’t eat anything!”], [“Mangiano poco.”, “They don’t eat much.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.09”, “content”: “Regular verbs in -ere are conjugated as follows:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Vendere”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “vendo”, “I sell”], [”(tu)”, “vendi”, “you sell”], [”(lui/lei)”, “vende”, “he/she/it sells”], [”(noi)”, “vendiamo”, “we sell”], [”(voi)”, “vendete”, “you sell”], [”(loro)”, “vendono”, “they sell”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Vendo il mio scooter.”, “I’m selling my scooter.”], [“Tu vendi il tuo?”, “Are you selling yours?”], [“Anna vende il suo.”, “Anna’s selling hers.”], [“Noi vendiamo la nostra casa.”, “We’re selling our house.”], [“Vendete molto?”, “Do you sell a lot?”], [“Loro vendono tutto.”, “They sell everything.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.10”, “content”: “Verbs ending in -cere, -gere, -scere (second conjugation) add an i before the endings of the second person singular (-i) and the first person plural (-iamo), in order to keep the soft sound of c, g and sc:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Conoscere”, “Leggere”, “Scegliere”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “conosco”, “I know”, “leggo”, “I read”, “scelgo”, “I choose”], [”(tu)”, “conosci”, “you know”, “leggi”, “you read”, “scegli”, “you choose”], [”(lui/lei)”, “conosce”, “he/she/it knows”, “legge”, “he/she/it reads”, “sceglie”, “he/she/it chooses”], [”(noi)”, “conosciamo”, “we know”, “leggiamo”, “we read”, “scegliamo”, “we choose”], [”(voi)”, “conoscete”, “you know”, “leggete”, “you read”, “scegliete”, “you choose”], [”(loro)”, “conoscono”, “they know”, “leggono”, “they read”, “scelgono”, “they choose”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Conosci Paolo?”, “Do you know Paolo?”], [“Noi conosciamo Anna.”, “We know Anna.”], [“Tu leggi molto?”, “Do you read a lot?”], [“Leggono il giornale.”, “They read the newspaper.”], [“Tu scegli?”, “Do you choose?”], [“Scegliamo noi.”, “We choose.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.11”, “content”: “Regular verbs in -ire are conjugated as follows:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Partire”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “parto”, “I leave/depart”], [”(tu)”, “parti”, “you leave/depart”], [”(lui/lei)”, “parte”, “he/she/it leaves/departs”], [”(noi)”, “partiamo”, “we leave/depart”], [”(voi)”, “partite”, “you leave/depart”], [”(loro)”, “partono”, “they leave/depart”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Parto domani.”, “I leave tomorrow.”], [“Tu parti presto?”, “Are you leaving early?”], [“Anna parte alle 8.”, “Anna leaves at 8.”], [“Partiamo fra un’ora.”, “We’re leaving in an hour.”], [“Voi partite con noi?”, “Are you leaving with us?”], [“Partono tutti.”, “They’re all leaving.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.12”, “content”: “Some verbs in -ire insert -isc- before the endings of the first, second and third persons singular and the third person plural:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Capire”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “capisco”, “I understand”], [”(tu)”, “capisci”, “you understand”], [”(lui/lei)”, “capisce”, “he/she/it understands”], [”(noi)”, “capiamo”, “we understand”], [”(voi)”, “capite”, “you understand”], [”(loro)”, “capiscono”, “they understand”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Capisco tutto.”, “I understand everything.”], [“Tu capisci?”, “Do you understand?”], [“Anna capisce.”, “Anna understands.”], [“Noi non capiamo.”, “We don’t understand.”], [“Capite l’italiano?”, “Do you understand Italian?”], [“Loro capiscono.”, “They understand.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.13”, “content”: “Here are some of the verbs that insert -isc-: aprire (to open), capire (to understand), finire (to finish/end), pulire (to clean), preferire (to prefer), seguire (to follow). Here are some verbs that do not insert -isc-: dormire (to sleep), partire (to leave), servire (to serve/need), scoprire (to discover), sentire (to hear), soffrire (to suffer), venire (to come).” }, { “id”: “5.14”, “content”: “As we saw in Unit 4, the pronouns used for the formal form are Lei for the singular (for both women and men) and Voi for the plural (the pronoun Loro is much more formal):”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [”(Lei) Parla italiano?”, “Do you speak Italian?”], [“Non prende un taxi, Professor Masi?”, “Aren’t you taking a taxi, Professor Masi?”], [“Partite, Signori Bianco?”, “Are you leaving(, Mr and Mrs Bianco)?”], [”((Loro) Partono, Signori Bianco?)”, “Are you leaving(, Mr and Mrs Bianco)?”] ] } } ] }, { “title”: “Present Tense of Some Irregular Verbs”, “paragraphs”: [ { “id”: “5.15”, “content”: “In Italian, as in most languages, there are a number of irregular verbs whose conjugation is best learned by heart and with use. Here is the conjugation of some of the more frequently used irregular verbs:”, “table”: { “headers”: [””, “Dare (to give)”, “Andare (to go)”, “Stare (to stay/live/feel)”, “Uscire (to go out/leave)”, “Sapere (to know)”, “Venire (to come)”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “dò”, “vado”, “sto”, “esco”, “so”, “vengo”], [”(tu)”, “dai”, “vai”, “stai”, “esci”, “sai”, “vieni”], [”(lui/lei)”, “dà”, “va”, “sta”, “esce”, “sa”, “viene”], [”(noi)”, “diamo”, “andiamo”, “stiamo”, “usciamo”, “sappiamo”, “veniamo”], [”(voi)”, “date”, “andate”, “state”, “uscite”, “sapete”, “venite”], [”(loro)”, “danno”, “vanno”, “stanno”, “escono”, “sanno”, “vengono”] ] } }, { “table”: { “headers”: [””, “Dovere (must/to have to)”, “Dire (to say/tell)”, “Potere (can/may/to be able)”, “Fare (to do/make)”, “Volere (to wish/to want)”, “Bere (to drink)”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “devo”, “dico”, “posso”, “faccio”, “voglio”, “bevo”], [”(tu)”, “devi”, “dici”, “puoi”, “fai”, “vuoi”, “bevi”], [”(lui/lei)”, “deve”, “dice”, “può”, “fa”, “vuole”, “beve”], [”(noi)”, “dobbiamo”, “diciamo”, “possiamo”, “facciamo”, “vogliamo”, “beviamo”], [”(voi)”, “dovete”, “dite”, “potete”, “fate”, “volete”, “bevete”], [”(loro)”, “devono”, “dicono”, “possono”, “fanno”, “vogliono”, “bevono”] ] } }, { “content”: “The verb riuscire (to succeed/manage/be able to) follows the same pattern as uscire.” }, { “id”: “5.16”, “content”: “ It is important not to confuse sapere and conoscere (paragraph 5.09). Both mean ‘to know’, but they are not always interchangeable. The basic difference is that sapere generally means ‘to know/be aware of/to have knowledge of a fact’ (but see also paragraph 5.17 below), whereas conoscere means ‘to be acquainted/familiar with’, or sometimes ‘to meet/make the acquaintance of’ (e.g. in the expression piacere di conoscerti, pleased to meet you). Thus sapere is never used for people, and conoscere is never followed by a phrase containing a verb:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Cosa fai?”, “What are you doing?”], [”‘Come stai?’ ‘Sto bene, grazie.’”, “‘How are you?’ ‘I’m fine, thank you.’”], [“Mia zia sta a Bologna.”, “My aunt lives in Bologna.”], [“Vado al cinema.”, “I’m going to the cinema.”], [“Stasera non esco.”, “I’m not going out tonight.”], [“Domani esco presto.”, “I’m leaving early tomorrow.”], [“Non riesco a capire.”, “I can’t understand.”], [“Non riesco a chiudere la porta.”, “I can’t manage to close the door.”], [“Adesso sapete tutto.”, “Now you know everything.”], [“Sappiamo già che c’è sciopero domani.”, “We already know that there is a strike tomorrow.”], [“Sai che ora è?”, “Do you know what time it is?”], [“Sai perché?”, “Do you know why?”], [“Non so che cosa fare.”, “I don’t know what to do.”], [“Conosco le regole del gioco.”, “I know the rules of the game.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.17”, “content”: “Dovere, potere and volere usually need to be followed by another verb in the infinitive:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Devo studiare.”, “I must study.”], [“Puoi venire?”, “Can you come?”], [“Voglio mangiare.”, “I want to eat.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.18”, “content”: “The verb sapere is another that is often followed by a verb in the infinitive; used in this way, it expresses the ability to do something (in the sense of ‘to know how to’ do something):”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Italian”, “English”], “rows”: [ [“Sai nuotare?”, “Do you know how to swim?”], [“Non sappiamo sciare.”, “We don’t know how to ski.”] ] } }, { “id”: “5.19”, “content”: “A few verbs end in -urre (like condurre (to lead/drive/manage), tradurre (to translate), produrre (to produce), etc.); all have the following pattern:”, “table”: { “headers”: [“Endings”, “Condurre”], “rows”: [ [”(io)”, “conduco”, “I lead/drive/manage”], [”(tu)”, “conduci”, “you lead/drive/manage”], [”(lui/lei)”, “conduce”, “he/she/it leads/drives/manages”], [”(noi)”, “conduciamo”, “we lead/drive/manage”], [”(voi)”, “conducete”, “you lead/drive/manage”], [”(loro)”, “conducono”, “they lead/drive/manage”] ] } } ] } ] }, “exercises”: [ { “title”: “Exercise 1: Present Tense of Verbs”, “instruction”: “Supply the present tense of the verb in brackets.”, “examples”: [”(noi) ___ italiani.”, “(tu) ___ scozzese?”], “items”: [ {“question”: “Claudio (arrivare) con il prossimo treno.”, “answer”: “arriva”}, {“question”: “Anna (vivere) a Roma.”, “answer”: “vive”}, {“question”: “Non (noi mangiare) spesso fuori.”, “answer”: “mangiamo”}, {“question”: “(tu cercare) casa?”, “answer”: “cerchi”}, {“question”: “Stasera (voi prendere) l’autobus.”, “answer”: “prendete”}, {“question”: “Il treno di Giorgio (partire) alle 18.”, “answer”: “parte”}, {“question”: “Tutti i giorni (noi leggere) il giornale.”, “answer”: “leggiamo”}, {“question”: “(tu pulire) il bagno?”, “answer”: “pulisci”}, {“question”: “(io conoscere) molti italiani.”, “answer”: “conosco”}, {“question”: “I giochi (finire) sempre alle 17.”, “answer”: “finiscono”}, {“question”: “Non (noi guidare) l’auto.”, “answer”: “guidiamo”}, {“question”: “Anna e io (giocare) a carte.”, “answer”: “giochiamo”}, {“question”: “Perché non (voi tornare) in Scozia?”, “answer”: “tornate”}, {“question”: “Non (tu capire) nulla!”, “answer”: “capisci”}, {“question”: “Giorgio e Paola non (spendere) molto.”, “answer”: “spendono”}, {“question”: “Dove (Lei abitare), Signor Verdi?”, “answer”: “abita”}, {“question”: “(Voi pagare) l’affitto, Signori Rossi?”, “answer”: “pagate”}, {“question”: “(tu viaggiare) molto.”, “answer”: “viaggi”}, {“question”: “Non (tu ricevere) molte lettere?”, “answer”: “ricevi”}, {“question”: “Piero e Gianni (lasciare) il cane a casa.”, “answer”: “lasciano”} ] }, { “title”: “Exercise 2: Present Tense of Verbs”, “instruction”: “Supply the present tense of the verb in brackets.”, “examples”: [”(noi) ___ italiani.”, “(tu) ___ scozzese?”], “items”: [ {“question”: “Stasera (loro) andare al cinema.”, “answer”: “vanno”}, {“question”: “La nostra fabbrica (produrre) pasta.”, “answer”: “produce”}, {“question”: “Domani (noi dare) una festa.”, “answer”: “diamo”}, {“question”: “(tu andare) spesso in spiaggia?”, “answer”: “vai”}, {“question”: “(io dovere) studiare stasera.”, “answer”: “devo”}, {“question”: “(voi volere) venire con noi?”, “answer”: “volete”}, {“question”: “(tu potere) aprire la porta?”, “answer”: “puoi”}, {“question”: “Non (io sapere) la risposta.”, “answer”: “so”}, {“question”: “(loro bere) solo acqua.”, “answer”: “bevono”}, {“question”: “(tu venire) alla festa?”, “answer”: “vieni”} ] }, { “title”: “Exercise 3: Translate into English”, “instruction”: “Translate the following sentences into English.”, “examples”: [”(noi) ___ italiani.”, “(tu) ___ scozzese?”], “items”: [ {“question”: “Non mangiate carne?”, “answer”: “Aren’t you eating meat?”}, {“question”: “Dove abita, Giorgio?”, “answer”: “Where do you live, Giorgio?”}, {“question”: “Non capisco l’italiano.”, “answer”: “I don’t understand Italian.”}, {“question”: “Anna e Paolo leggono molto.”, “answer”: “Anna and Paolo read a lot.”}, {“question”: “Non vogliamo uscire stasera.”, “answer”: “We don’t want to go out this evening.”}, {“question”: “Puoi venire domani?”, “answer”: “Can you come tomorrow?”}, {“question”: “Bevo solo caffè.”, “answer”: “I drink only coffee.”}, {“question”: “Perché non andate a Firenze, Claudio?”, “answer”: “Why don’t you go to Florence, Claudio?”}, {“question”: “Escono spesso la sera.”, “answer”: “They go out often in the evening.”}, {“question”: “I ragazzi giocano a calcio domani.”, “answer”: “The boys play football tomorrow.”} ] } ], { “title”: “Exercise 4: Translate into Italian”, “instruction”: “Translate the following sentences into Italian.”, “examples”: [”(noi) ___ italiani.”, “(tu) ___ scozzese?”], “items”: [ {“question”: “Are you going out tonight, Mother?”, “answer”: “Esci stasera, mamma?”}, {“question”: “What are we doing tomorrow?”, “answer”: “Che facciamo domani?”}, {“question”: “Can you [sing.] open that door?”, “answer”: “Puoi aprire quella porta?”}, {“question”: “Do you [sing.] want a coffee?”, “answer”: “Vuoi un caffè?”}, {“question”: “Can you play the piano, Francesco?”, “answer”: “Sai suonare il piano, Francesco?”}, {“question”: “What are you [sing.] looking for?”, “answer”: “Che cerchi?”}, {“question”: “Are you [polite] drinking coffee or mineral water, Madam?”, “answer”: “Beve caffè o acqua minerale, Signora?”}, {“question”: “Do you [sing.] and Jim know my parents?”, “answer”: “Tu e Jim conoscete i miei genitori?”}, {“question”: “Are you [sing.] well today?”, “answer”: “Stai bene oggi?”}, {“question”: “What are they building?”, “answer”: “Che costruiscono?”} ] }, { “title”: “Exercise 5: Translate into Italian”, “instruction”: “Translate the following sentences into Italian.”, “examples”: [”(noi) ___ italiani.”, “(tu) ___ scozzese?”], “items”: [ {“question”: “Don’t you [polite] speak English, Mrs Vialli?”, “answer”: “Non parla inglese, Signora Vialli?”}, {“question”: “My German friends can’t sing in Italian.”, “answer”: “I miei amici tedeschi non sanno cantare in italiano.”}, {“question”: “I don’t earn a lot.”, “answer”: “Non guadagno molto.”}, {“question”: “Isn’t she giving a party for her birthday?”, “answer”: “Non dà una festa per il suo compleanno?”}, {“question”: “Aren’t you [sing.] working with Giulia?”, “answer”: “Non lavori con Giulia?”}, {“question”: “They’ve not seen Mr Moro for three years.”, “answer”: “Non vedono il signor Moro da tre anni.”}, {“question”: “Why do you never go to Florence, Claudio?”, “answer”: “Perché non vai mai a Firenze, Claudio?”}, {“question”: “I can’t manage to shut this window.”, “answer”: “Non riesco a chiudere questa finestra.”}, {“question”: “Why aren’t you [pl.] drinking coffee this morning?”, “answer”: “Perché non bevete caffè stamattina?”}, {“question”: “Aren’t you [pl.] coming tomorrow?”, “answer”: “Non venite domani?”} ] } ] } }
